@Kareem Ayas 

You're welcome!

Congratulations on a well-deserved win! Keep the fun puzzles coming!

@Lewis 

You're welcome, Lewis! 

I'm glad you found the voting process easy. That was one of my goals.

@john ezra 

It was a pleasure working with both you and CLM.

I second your suggestion about keeping a running list of one's favorite puzzles throughout the year. Someone suggested making screenshots of the grids; another way to do it painlessly would be to copy the links to the puzzles' write-ups here, on xwordinfo.com, or on crosswordfiend.com.

@Lex Milar 

Just about anytime you think there's an error, especially a spelling error, in the puzzle, that's a sign that there is some tomfoolery afoot.  Rebuses.  Answers that don't strictly mean anything when read up/down or right/left, where you have to divert from the straight paths to find the true answer.  Tricks like that.

In fact, that's a tip off, for those people who often ask for a sign of rebuses.  Look for ONE answer that you are dead sure of, like I was RACHELWEISZ.  The fact that there was a space missing was a sure sign one space had two letters in it.

@Puzzlemucker 

"Because we need to continue to sleep and have fun if we want this revolution to have staying power."

Amen, brother puzzler.

@Doug 

I think this was a "can't see the forest for the trees" moment by early the repliers to your post.  ;)

I understood your OP in the context you described, in the first reading without need for further elucidation. But TBH I didn't see either of those entries in that context during my solve -- and additionally, in his notes the constructor said this puzzle was initiated way back in 2022. Of course the Promise Keepers were a known thing back then, but certainly DOGE didn't yet exist!

@J
If you haven’t heard of PDQ Bach, the creation of musicologist Peter Schickele, this is your chance. Check your music source for any of his albums. We used to go to annual concerts of his classical music spoofs at Carnegie hall every year. My favorite work was Concerto for Horn and Hardart just for the name. Or The Hoarse Trojan. Or Iphigenia in Brooklyn.

L

@Anita so the clue is DENVER for STAGE NAME…because whenever we see Denver, we understand it is a stage name?

How about next time, the Times puzzle says ACTOR and we just accept that whichever actor they use as the answer is the correct one?

Really, defending or accepting this answer for an otherwise clever puzzle is insulting.

@Desert Dweller hard disagree. This was my favorite clue of the puzzle. 

“ whenever we see Denver, we understand it is a stage name?” Of course not. It’s a clue for this puzzle. And a really clever one at that. 

Also, “actor/Colorado” makes no sense in the context of the other clues.

@Desert Dweller 
It was 'Denver' in this context that was the dead giveaway. 

For me, I knew that DENVER had to mean something one letter off from STATE NAME and it could not mean the city. Because the state was COLORADO, I immediately thought of Rocky Mountain High and John Denver. So 'John Denver' had to be something a letter off from STATE NAME. Ah, he was a performer, so it was probably a stage name. And G fit the down answer.

@Wendy 

Get back to us when you've completed the puzzle and have sorted out the theme.

Hint:  When you find an "error" as blatant as this one, it might be a rebus.

@Sarah 

