@Emkay 

You may have listened to PDQ Bach, but it is unlikely that you played his music. 

We attended a concert by him in Princeton with our kids when they were adolescents. It was hysterical. It began with  an announcement (sounding like a flight attendant) explaining how to find the exits, while ushers stood in the aisles, pointing to them, a la flight attendants, and explaining what to do if oxygen masks fell from the chandeliers. Peter Schickele, who claimed to be a relative of the fictional baroque composer PDQ Bach, was a musical comedian par excellence. If your piano teacher exposed you to his work, along with the real JS Bach, she or he was a teach with a great sense of humor!

@Mark 
WARD is one of those odd words (like cleave) that can mean the opposite of itself. I'm sure there's a name for that, but I don't know it. So a ward of the state requires a keeper, but a ward in older usage can be the keeper. See also; warden or warder, or to ward off evil. TIL that it comes from the Saxon weard, for watchman.

Best wishes on your procedure.

