@Barry Ancona 

Sometimes, what makes a puzzle fun to make (“twistyness,” intricacy, niche references) is at odds with what makes them fun to solve. Many constructors frequently speak of enjoying the complexity and obscurity of their creations—it’s common for seasoned solvers to move into the constructor space seeking challenge and novelty. This doesn’t necessarily lend itself to a fun solve, however, particularly for less experienced solvers or those looking for more casual puzzling.

Put another way, the hedge maze designer at the Overlook Hotel may have delighted in the sprawling and interminable construction of their masterpiece, but that doesn’t mean Jack enjoyed it.

